from 1175 to 1184","about 1197":"about 1197","1207":"1207","Carlisle, Cumberland, England":"Carlisle, Cumberland, England","Freston, Suffolk, England":"Freston, Suffolk, England","Gilsland, Northumberland, England":"Gilsland, Northumberland, England","Irthington, Cumberland, England":"Irthington, Cumberland, England","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Vaux","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of various places in northern France called Vaux, from the Old French plural of <i>val</i> ‘valley’. Compare English   Vause   and French   Devaux  .","History: Richard Vaux (1749–90) emigrated from Sussex, England, to Philadelphia, PA, in early youth. Calvert Vaux, landscape architect, emigrated from London, England, to America in 1850 and designed several major US parks, including Central Park in New York City (with Frederick Olmstead). — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors (along with its variant <i>Veaux</i> and altered form   Devoe  ) and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America."],"variants":[{"name":"Vause","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire):","of Norman origin, a habitational name from Vaux (see   Vaux  ), a common French placename, singular and plural of <i>val</i> ‘valley’, the plural form being Latinized in surnames as <i>de Vallibus</i>. Norman lords with this surname are recorded in 12th- and early 13th-century records in Cumberland (Irthington), Devon (Farwood, in Colyton), East Yorkshire (Warter), Essex (Belchamp), and Leicestershire (Belvoir). Compare   Vale  .","nickname perhaps from Middle English <i>fals</i>, <i>faus</i>, <i>vaus</i> (Old French <i>fals</i>, <i>faus</i>, Old English <i>fals</i>) ‘deceitful, disloyal, dishonest, mendacious’, but it is more likely the name arises from 1, with the common Anglo-Norman French substitution of <i>le</i> for <i>de</i> in their surname."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":40,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":49,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":84,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":115,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Maud de Vaux of Cumberland was born from 1175 to 1184, in Carlisle, Cumberland, England. She married Robert de Vaux VI about 1189, in Cumberland, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in Gilsland, Northumberland, England."},"et":{"from 1175 to 1184–":"1175 kuni 1184–Surnud","1170–1235":"1170–1235","1190–1240":"1190–1240","1197–Male":"1197–Surnud","1207–1269":"1207–1269","1175–Female":"1175–Surnud","1190":"1190","1175":"1175","1197":"1197","1240":"1240","1170":"1170","1290":"1290","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1269":"1269","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","about 1189":"umbes 1189","from 1175 to 118